<section class="guidelines landing-guide" id="guidelines">
    <div class="help-header"><h2>Bass Test Guide</h2><p>Safe, step-by-step checks for subwoofers, studio monitors, and bass-capable headphones.</p></div>
    <div class="help-grid">
        <div class="help-card"><h3>Step 1: set a safe volume</h3><ol><li>Start with system volume at 20-30% before pressing Start.</li><li>Low frequencies move a lot of cone mass &mdash; at high volume they can damage small drivers.</li><li>Raise volume slowly, only if you hear nothing.</li></ol></div>
        <div class="help-card"><h3>Step 2: pick a mode</h3><ol><li><strong>Sweep</strong> auto-ramps 20 Hz &rarr; 200 Hz over the duration you choose.</li><li><strong>Step</strong> plays ISO 1/3-octave presets: 20, 25, 31, 40, 50, 63, 80, 100, 125, 160, 200 Hz.</li><li><strong>Hold</strong> lets you drag the slider freely between 20 and 200 Hz.</li></ol></div>
        <div class="help-card"><h3>Step 3: listen for artefacts</h3><ol><li>Rattles, buzzing, or cabinet vibration between 40-100 Hz usually mean a loose driver, grille, or enclosure.</li><li>Sudden silence below 40 Hz on a laptop or earbud is expected &mdash; the driver has hit its physical limit.</li><li>Clean, continuous tone across the full sweep = your system is reproducing bass correctly.</li></ol></div>
        <div class="help-card"><h3>Common issues</h3><ul><li>Only a hiss below 60 Hz &rarr; speaker is undersized, try a subwoofer or larger monitor.</li><li>Distortion that grows with volume &rarr; drop volume until the tone is clean, that is your safe ceiling.</li><li>One channel quieter &rarr; pick Left only / Right only to isolate which speaker is underperforming.</li></ul></div>
